Introduction

In todayâ€™s fast-paced financial markets, understanding and anticipating stock behaviour is critical for investors, traders, and analysts. This study investigates the time series dynamics of NVIDIA (NVDA) by examining its adjusted stock prices, volatility, and trading volume. We use both new forecasting approaches (namely, Metaâ€™s Prophet model) and traditional statistical methods like linear regression and STL decomposition. By integrating these methods, we want to not only estimate future trends but also break down the time series into its core components: trend, seasonality, and residuals.

Data and Methodology

Data Acquisition

Yahoo Finance was used to gather historical data on NVIDIA for this project. The dataset covers the period from January 1, 2015 to the present, and includes daily adjusted closing prices and trading volume. We calculated daily log returns and used a 30-day rolling window to estimate volatility. Our time series analyses are based on these measurements.

Forecasting with Prophet

Prophet is a powerful forecasting tool that identifies patterns, seasonality, and holiday effects in time series data. In our investigation, we constructed distinct Prophet models for daily and monthly data.

  • Daily Forecasts:
    We used Prophet to predict daily volatility and trade volume. The projections include a shaded confidence interval, indicating the degree of uncertainty in our estimates. In addition, linear regression trends are overlayed on the historical data, acting as a baseline to validate Prophetâ€™s forecasts.

  • Monthly Forecasts:
    Monthly Forecasts: To reduce noise, we aggregated daily data to a monthly level. This method highlights long-term seasonal trends while smoothing out short-term swings. Both average monthly volatility and total monthly trade volume are modeled and anticipated with Prophet.

Classical Methods: Linear Regression and STL Decomposition

In addition to Prophet, we used linear regression on all charts to provide an intuitive view of long-term trends. Linear regression provides a simple baseline to compare against Prophetâ€™s more sophisticated projections.

Furthermore, we used STL (Seasonal-Trend decomposition with Loess) on the monthly aggregates. The STL decomposition divides the time series into three components:

  • Trend: The long-term movement.
  • Seasonal: The repeating periodic fluctuations.
  • Residual: The noise or irregular variation.

We also calculated seasonal amplitude (the difference between the maximum and minimum values of the seasonal component) to assess the significance of seasonal variations in our data.

Monthly Analysis

Aggregated Metrics

By combining daily data into monthly figures, we can get smoother and more interpretable trends. Monthly analysis focuses on:

  • Average Volatility: The average volatility for each month.

  • Total Trading Volume: The aggregate of daily volumes for the entire month.

  • Monthly Volatility:

This graphic highlights seasonal variations and long-term shifts in market uncertainty. The regression line clearly indicates whether volatility is growing or decreasing over time.

  • Monthly Trading Volume:
    The monthly trading volume chart sums the total volume for the month and overlays a linear regression trend.

This visualisation shows long-term investor activity trends. It is beneficial for analysing overall market liquidity trends and detecting seasonal spikes or decreases in trading activity.

Seasonal Decomposition

STL decomposition is used on monthly aggregated data to divide the time series into trend, seasonal, and residual components.

The Trend Component reveals the underlying long-term movement.

Seasonal Component: Displays repeated patterns throughout a one-year cycle. The seasonal amplitude (the difference between maximum and minimum) measures the magnitude of these seasonal changes.

The residual component captures random noise that is not explained by trend or seasonality.

For example, the decomposition of monthly average volatility demonstrates the cyclical character of market uncertainty, whereas the breakdown of monthly trading volume reveals seasonal fluctuations in investor behaviour.

The seasonal amplitude (difference between maximum and minimum of the seasonal component) quantifies how large the seasonal variations are. This provides insight into the importance of seasonality in NVIDIAâ€™s market behaviour.
